ents required by the schema rather than as the primary energy source. This is a network-connecting abstraction grounded in Johnson et al. (2009)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formose-type production of glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pools with wet-dry concentration; borate stabilization of carbohydrate products"}, "mechanism": "Condensation/homologation of one-carbon carbonyls generates C2 sugar precursors stabilized by borate-rich settings.", "reasoning": "The deep research report notes formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde as ubiquitous feedstocks and acknowledges formose-type chemistry as a plausible upstream source of higher sugars, although not valine-specific. This connecting step is used to ground the Patel et al. (2015) glyceraldehyde-dependent cyanosulfidic route in a surface environment compatible with the supplied framework. It is therefore supportive but not directly demonstrated as a valine-specific step (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Aldol/formose extension from glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "sunlit evaporitic or geothermal pools; borate stabilization of triose products"}, "mechanism": "Aldol extension of C1/C2 carbonyl chemistry yields triose sugars, with borate suppressing uncontrolled decomposition.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) explicitly use glyceraldehyde as an entry point to the valine/leucine aminonitrile homologation network. The report highlights glyceraldehyde as a key precursor and notes its connection to dihydroxyacetone and acetone. This upstream generation from simpler carbonyls is included as a necessary connecting reaction compatible with the reported chemistry, though less directly established for valine than later steps (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photoredox conversion of glyceraldehyde to dihydroxyacetone and acetone pool", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (copper sulfide/cuprous sulfide)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature to 300K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) sulfide photoredox system on sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; phosphate-buffered sulfidic pond; dark/light cycles"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven HCN/H2S/Cu photoredox chemistry interconverts triose carbonyl pools, yielding dihydroxyacetone and acetone derivatives feeding branched aminonitrile synthesis.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) describe glyceraldehyde entering a dark/photochemical sequence in the presence of HCN, H2S, phosphate, and Cu photoredox catalysts, with dihydroxyacetone and acetone appearing as key intermediates toward the branched valine aminonitrile pathway. The report explicitly identifies glyceraldehyde, dihydroxyacetone, and acetone in this sequence (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "HCN addition to acetone to form acetone cyanohydrin", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (copper sulfide/cuprous sulfide)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu sulfide-assisted cyanosulfidic conditions", "aqueous": "true", "other": "dark addition followed by UV-enabled downstream processing; H2S present in system"}, "mechanism": "Reversible