sistent with the report's emphasis on branched C4 carbonyl supply being an open question (Patel et al., 2015; Miller & Schlesinger, 1993)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Ammonia addition to branched cyanohydrin intermediate to form valine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (copper sulfide/cuprous sulfide)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface-assisted ammonia addition in cyanosulfidic pond setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "post-UV aqueous ammonia addition; phosphate-buffered conditions"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic ammonia addition to the branched cyanohydrin-derived precursor yields the alpha-aminonitrile corresponding to valine precursor 27.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) directly report that ammonia addition to intermediate 26 affords valine aminonitrile 27 in approximately 42% yield. This is a core literature-supported step in the valine cyanosulfidic pathway (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Classical Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde to valine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface concentration on clay and phosphate-rich drying pools", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral-to-basic pH about 8-10; concentrated cyanide and ammonia in evaporitic or geothermal ponds"}, "mechanism": "Isobutyraldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, cyanide adds to give the alpha-aminonitrile valine precursor.", "reasoning": "Miller & Schlesinger (1993) explicitly identify isobutyraldehyde as the Strecker precursor to valine, and the deep research report summarizes the standard mechanism as aldehyde plus NH3 plus HCN to valine aminonitrile. The environmental pH requirement and prebiotic context are also summarized in the report (Miller & Schlesinger, 1993; Powner et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "DAP-enabled neutral-pH Strecker variant from isobutyraldehyde to valine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "diamidophosphate in neutral water with phosphate-rich mineral setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "near-neutral pH around 7; drying-rewetting cycles compatible with reduced phosphorus chemistry"}, "mechanism": "DAP transiently activates the carbonyl/ammonia/cyanide system through phosphoroaminonitrile formation, enabling aminonitrile synthesis without strongly basic bulk solution.", "reasoning": "Powner et al. (2019) showed that diamidophosphate promotes Strecker-type synthesis at neutral pH, giving N-phosphoro-aminonitriles in high yield from aldehydes and HCN. The deep research report specifically notes that by analogy this chemistry could enable valine formation from isobutyraldehyde under mild conditions. This is therefore a literature-guided analogical extension rather than a valine-specific direct demonstration, but it follows the report's instructions closely (Powner et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-400K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "water-catalyzed hydrolysis during heating, pond cycling, or acidic/basic episodes"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise nitrile hydration and hydrolysis converts the alpha-aminonitrile into the corresponding alpha-amino acid valine.", "reasoning": "The deep research report identifies hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile as the canonical final