k\": \"The cross-environment flow is good, but the weakest step in the whole network appears here: direct hydrothermal generation of formaldehyde from CO2 and H2 is not a well-established vent product in the cited valine literature, and hydrothermal systems more strongly support formate/acetate/pyruvate than free formaldehyde. Downstream surface chemistry is plausible, but the hydrothermal feedstock choice reduces confidence.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_001\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_007\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Replace direct formaldehyde production with a more defensible hydrothermal feedstock route or atmospheric source\",\n        \"Explicitly justify transfer from hydrothermal output to surface concentration pools\",\n        \"Expand cyanosulfidic transformations into stepwise literature-matched reactions\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.42,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.82\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.76,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.79,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.83,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.77,\n      \"feedback\": \"The terminal Strecker portion is strong, but the upstream 'formose-seeded' logic does not convincingly solve the literature-identified bottleneck of generating branched aldehydes like isobutyraldehyde. Formose chemistry can produce sugars, but not efficiently the specific branched C4 aldehyde needed for valine. This pathway therefore has a major precursor gap.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_001\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Do not imply that formose chemistry naturally leads to isobutyraldehyde without explicit support\",\n        \"Introduce a literature-sup