 1993; Patel et al., 2015; Powner et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"DAP-enabled neutral-pH phosphoro-Strecker activation of isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"diamidophosphate with phosphate-rich mineral matrix\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral water, pH ~7; drying-rewetting compatible; DAP masks/activates ammonia and cyanide chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"DAP transiently activates the carbonyl/amine/cyanide system through phosphoroaminonitrile-type intermediates, allowing aminonitrile formation at near-neutral pH.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Powner and co-workers showed DAP can promote Strecker-type phosphoroaminonitrile formation in neutral water in high yield, solving the free-NH3/high-pH constraint of traditional Strecker chemistry. Applying the same logic to isobutyraldehyde is literature-consistent by analogy and remains one of the most plausible mild-surface variants for valine aminonitrile generation (Powner et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photoredox conversion of glyceraldehyde to dihydroxyacetone and acetone pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"290-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox on copper sulfide mineral surfaces with UV assistance\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\