d downstream networks (Johnson et al., 2009)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Classical Strecker formation of valine aminonitrile from isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_002", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite; divalent cation-rich mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous shallow pool; neutral-to-basic pH ~8-10; concentrated cyanide and free NH3 favored"}, "mechanism": "Isobutyraldehyde forms an imine with NH3, cyanide adds to the iminium, and the resulting aminonitrile accumulates prior to hydrolysis.", "reasoning": "This is the canonical prebiotic route to valine from the literature: isobutyraldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor to valine, proceeding through valine aminonitrile. High-pH aqueous conditions are consistent with the need for free NH3. Mineral concentration by clays is plausible though valine-specific catalysis is limited; the route itself is directly grounded in the Strecker discussion for valine (Miller & Schlesinger, 1993; Powner et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "water-rich pools; prolonged heating or geochemical cycling promotes nitrile hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile undergoes stepwise hydration and hydrolysis to the corresponding carboxylic acid, yielding valine.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the accepted terminal step of Strecker chemistry. The valine-specific precursor is the aminonitrile identified in Strecker and cyanosulfidic studies; hydrolysis then furnishes valine. This step is standard and required to connect the experimentally observed aminonitrile to the amino acid target (Miller & Schlesinger, 1993; Patel et al., 2015; Powner et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "DAP-enabled neutral-pH phosphoro-Strecker activation of isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_002", "mol_001", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "diamidophosphate with phosphate-rich mineral matrix", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral water, pH ~7; drying-rewetting compatible; DAP masks/activates ammonia and cyanide chemistry"}, "mechanism": "DAP transiently activates the carbonyl/amine/cyanide system through phosphoroaminonitrile-type intermediates, allowing aminonitrile formation at near-neutral pH.", "reasoning": "Powner and co-workers showed DAP can promote Strecker-type phosphoroaminonitrile formation in neutral water in high yield, solving the free-NH3/high-pH constraint of traditional Strecker chemistry. Applying the same logic to isobutyraldehyde is literature-consistent by analogy and remains one of the most plausible mild-surface variants for valine aminonitrile generation (Powner et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface photoredox conversion of glyceraldehyde to dihydroxyacetone and acetone pool", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "290-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox on copper sulfide mineral surfaces with UV assistance", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; H2S/HS- reductant; phosphate-buffered pond chemistry; stepwise dark/photochemical cycling"}, "mechanism": "Under UV and sulfide photoredox conditions, glyceraldehyde enters a homologation/fragmentation network that yields dihydroxyacetone and acetone as branch-forming intermediates.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. established that glyceraldehyde and its acetone byproducts participate in the cyanosulfidic network leading to branched aminonitriles including the valine precursor. Copper sulfide photoredox is central in the original system; the surface mineral category used here reflects the required sulfide-mineral mediation while preserving the reported UV/H2S chemistry (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation from acetone and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "290-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) sulfide-associated photoredox environment", "aqueous": "true", "other": "dark cyanohydrin addition step embedded in cyanosulfidic sequence; reversible unless trapped downstream"}, "mechanism": "HCN adds reversibly to acetone to form the corresponding cyanohydrin, which is trapped by subsequent sulfide chemistry.", "reasoning": "Acetone cyanohydrin is an explicitly described entry point in Patel's branched amino-acid route. The addition of HCN to acetone is reversible but becomes productive when coupled to the following hydrosulfide trapping step, matching the cyanosulfidic mechanism (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydrosulfide trapping of acetone cyanohydrin to alpha-hydroxythioamide", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "290-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu-sulfide mediated HS- chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "dark step in H2S/HS- rich pond; phosphate-buffered cyanosulfidic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Hydrosulfide converts the cyanohydrin into an alpha-hydroxythioamide, channeling material away from reversal and into the photoredox branch-building sequence.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. specifically report conversion of cyanohydrin intermediates to alpha-hydroxythioamides under dark HS- addition conditions. This step is essential to the experimentally mapped route toward valine aminonitrile and should not be collapsed away if literature fidelity is required (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "UV/H2S photoreduction of alpha-hydroxythioamide to thioamide", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "290-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) sulfide photoredox system", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; H2S reductant; room-temperature pond conditions"}, "mechanism": "Photoredox reduction under UV and sulfide removes oxygen functionality and advances the intermediate to a thioamide stage poised for aldehyde/cyanohydrin re-entry.", "reasoning": "This step follows the Patel sequence in which alpha-hydroxythioamides are photochemically reduced to thioamides under UV/H2S in the presence of copper sulfide photoredox chemistry. It is one of the experimentally validated branch-building transformations in the valine precursor route (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Continuation of cyanosulfidic sequence to valine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "290-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) sulfide photoredox system", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV plus dark cycles; aldehyde generation and trapping as cyanohydrin 26 followed by NH3 addition to aminonitrile 27; reported one-step 26 to 27 yield ~42%"}, "mechanism": "The thioamide is photoch