rk connection rather than a dominant synthetic source"}, "mechanism": "Amino acid/keto acid interconversion links valine and its cognate alpha-keto acid, reflecting metabolism-like reversible chemistry.", "reasoning": "The literature identifies alpha-ketoisovalerate as the transamination partner and immediate precursor/product pair with valine. This reaction is included to express the experimentally and biochemically recognized relationship between the two compounds, while acknowledging that prebiotic transamination efficiency remains less directly established than the Ni-catalyzed forward hydrogenation (Miller & Schlesinger, 1993; Kaur et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Miller-Urey-type spark discharge direct formation of valine in complex mixture", "inputs": ["mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "localized 800-1200C spark, bulk cooling to ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "aqueous": "false", "other": "reducing gas mixture such as CH4/NH3/H2O with electrical discharge and subsequent aqueous collection"}, "mechanism": "Complex radical, nitrile, and Strecker-like discharge chemistry generates amino acids directly as a mixture, including trace valine.", "reasoning": "Johnson et al. reanalysis of Miller's samples detected valine among many amino acids formed in spark-discharge experiments. This route is retained as a validated but low-selectivity direct environmental pathway. Because the deep research explicitly lists spark-discharge as one of the main validated routes, it is included despite low yield and mechanistic complexity (Johnson et al., 2009)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Classical Strecker to valine", "description": "Canonical aqueous Strecker sequence from isobutyraldehyde via valine aminonitrile followed by hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003"], "key_intermediates": [