      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.42\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.38,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.45,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.52,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.7,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.49,\n      \"feedback\": \"The literature supports direct detection of valine in spark-discharge mixtures, but the network representation is chemically inadequate because NH3 alone is not an appropriate sole input to valine formation. This reaction omits key feedstocks such as CH4, H2O, and discharge energy, and therefore fails as a properly specified bipartite network reaction.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_012\",\n        \"rxn_001\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Represent spark discharge as a complex atmospheric mixture with explicit gas inputs and energy source\",\n        \"Do not encode direct amino acid production from NH3 alone\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.78,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"The network is strong in literature awareness and captures the three major validated valine routes: Strecker via isobutyraldehyde, cyanosulfidic photochemistry via aminonitrile intermediates, and Ni-catalyzed reductive amination from alpha-ketoisovalerate. It also correctly highlights the key bottlenecks identified in the literature, especially precursor availability. Topologically, the graph is connected and has good convergence at valine aminonitrile and valine. However, there are important issues. First, several declared hub molecules are weakly justified as hubs, especially glyceraldehyde and alpha-ketoisovalerate, and the reported convergence count appears inflated. Second, some reactions are chemically under-specified or compressed, especially the cyanosulfidic sequence and the spark-discharge nodes. Third, the network does not satisfy the original synthesis-network requirement that all hydrothermal and surface reactions specify mineral agents; copper sulfides and Ni minerals should be explicit, and surface mineral agents are largely missing. Fourth, rxn_001 and rxn_012 are especially weakly encoded and do not properly represent atmospheric discharge chemistry. Overall, the network is scientifically informed and several individual pathways are approvable, but as a complete synthesis network it falls short of full approval because of missing mineral specification, compressed reaction detail, and a few improperly specified reactions.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.73,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.84\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_002": 0.86, "rxn_003": 0.9}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.88, "pathway_coherence": 0.92, "environmental_progression": 0.82, "target_achievement": 0.95, "overall_confidence": 0.89, "feedback": "This is the strongest canonical route in the network. Classical Strecker formation of valine aminonitrile from isobutyraldehyde, NH3, and HCN is well aligned with the literature, and hydrolysis of the aminonitrile to valine is chemically standard. Main limitation is that the network does not explain the prebiotic source of isobutyraldehyde, which the literature identifies as a major open problem.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": [], "suggestions": ["Add a literature-grounded source pathway for isobutyraldehyde or explicitly mark it as an exogenous precursor bottleneck", "Specify mineral agents for the surface Strecker step to satisfy schema and environmental requirements"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_004": 0.9, "rxn_003": 0.9}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.9, "pathway_coherence": 0.93, "environmental_progression": 0.86, "target_achievement": 0.95, "overall_confidence": 0.91, "feedback": "DAP-enabled neutral-pH Strecker chemistry is well aligned with the cited neutral-water phosphoroaminonitrile literature and