ed in the literature", "Avoid presenting partial-pathway shortcuts as fully validated target routes"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_003": 0.9}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.9, "pathway_coherence": 0.55, "environmental_progression": 0.4, "target_achievement": 0.95, "overall_confidence": 0.68, "feedback": "Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine is chemically sound, but this is not a complete synthesis pathway because it omits the essential upstream generation of the aminonitrile. It is better interpreted as a convergence endpoint than a standalone pathway.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": [], "suggestions": ["Reclassify this as a terminal conversion module rather than a distinct full pathway", "Only count complete source-to-target routes as pathways"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_012": 0.42}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.38, "pathway_coherence": 0.45, "environmental_progression": 0.52, "target_achievement": 0.7, "overall_confidence": 0.49, "feedback": "The literature supports direct detection of valine in spark-discharge mixtures, but the network representation is chemically inadequate because NH3 alone is not an appropriate sole input to valine formation. This reaction omits key feedstocks such as CH4, H2O, and discharge energy, and therefore fails as a properly specified bipartite network reaction.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_012", "rxn_001"], "suggestions": ["Represent spark discharge as a complex atmospheric mixture with explicit gas inputs and energy source", "Do not encode direct amino acid production from NH3 alone"]}], "best_pathway_id": "P2", "overall_confidence": 0.78, "network_feedback": "The network is strong in literature awareness and captures the three major validated valine routes: Strecker via isobutyraldehyde, cyanosulfidic photochemistry via aminonitrile intermediates, and Ni-catalyzed reductive amination from alpha-ketoisovalerate. It also correctly highlights the key bottlen