e minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic or geothermal pools; UV-exposed; borate stabilizes higher sugars"}, "mechanism": "Aldol/formose-type homologation of formaldehyde produces C2-C3 sugars, with borate complexation stabilizing glyceraldehyde and related aldoses.", "reasoning": "The deep research notes that small sugars such as glyceraldehyde are key entry points to Patel-type cyanosulfidic chemistry and that formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde are plausible prebiotic feedstocks, while acknowledging that branched products are not directly favored by generalized formose chemistry. This step is therefore limited to experimentally and mechanistically plausible sugar generation feeding the Patel pathway, not to direct branched valine skeleton construction (Patel et al., 2015; deep research synthesis)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photoredox conversion of glyceraldehyde to acetone", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (copper sulfide / Cu2S-like)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature to ~300K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox on sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; phosphate-buffered cyanosulfidic setting; sequential dark/photochemical cycles"}, "mechanism": "Glyceraldehyde enters a Cu-sulfide/H2S-driven photoredox network that generates dihydroxyacetone and acetone as experimentally observed branch-point carbonyl products.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. 2015 explicitly identify glyceraldehyde-derived acetone chemistry as part of the homologation route to valine aminonitrile. The deep research states that glyceraldehyde partly decays or is photoredox-converted to dihydroxyacetone and acetone, which then enter cyanohydrin/thioamide chemistry. This is represented as a condensed but literature-grounded step feeding acetone, rather than as an invented alternative route (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Acetone cyanohydrin formation", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (copper sulfide / Cu2S-like)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "copper sulfide-associated cyanosulfidic setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "dark cyanohydrin addition; reversible step in HCN-rich ponds"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of cyanide to acetone forms acetone cyanohydrin, establishing the branched carbon skeleton used in the Patel sequence.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. 2015 describe addition of HCN to acetone to form cyanohydrin 23 as the entry to the valine/leucine branch of the cyanosulfidic network. This step is directly grounded in the reported mechanism and is kept separate to avoid the excessive compression criticized in previous attempts (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrosulfide trapping of acetone cyanohydrin to alpha-hydroxythioamide", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (copper sulfide / Cu2S-like)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "copper sulfide photoredox environment", "aqueous": "true", "other": "dark HS- addition in sulfidic aqueous solution"}, "mechanism": "Hydrosulfide addition converts the cyanohydrin into an alpha-hydroxythioamide intermediate, kinetically trapping the branched framework for subsequent photoreduction.", "reasoning": "The deep research specifically notes that acetone cyanohydrin converts under dark HS- addition to alpha-hydroxythioamide intermediate 24. This is an experimentally observed Patel-network step and is explicitly represented to preserve literature fidelity (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "UV photoreduction of alpha-hydroxythioamide to branched thioamide", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (copper sulfide / Cu2S-like)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) sulfide photoredox system", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation with H2S as reductant"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven reduction and sulfur-mediated rearrangement converts the alpha-hydroxythioamide to the corresponding branched thioamide.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. 2015 report UV/H2S conversion of hydroxylthioamide intermediates to thioamides in the valine precursor sequence. This step preserves the experimentally supported sequence and avoids collapsing multiple transformations into a single unsupported node (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "UV/H2S homologation of branched thioamide to valine cyanohydrin intermediate 26", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_004", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (copper sulfide / Cu2S-like)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu-sulfide photoredox system", "aqueous": "true", "other": "continued UV irradiation; H2S reductant; HCN traps aldehydic intermediate as cyanohydrin"}, "mechanism": "Photoreduction of the thioamide generates a branched aldehydic intermediate that is trapped by HCN as cyanohydrin 26; free isobutyraldehyde is represented as a connected branch because the same branched aldehyde framework underlies both Patel and Strecker routes.", "reasoning": "The deep research states that continued UV/H2S chemistry converts the thioamide toward an aldehyde, which is then trapped by HCN as cyanohydrin 26; this leads directly to valine aminonitrile upon NH3 addition. Isobutyraldehyde is included as a connected branch-point because Miller & Schlesinger identify it as the Strecker precursor to valine, and the Patel sequence transiently passes through an equivalent branched aldehydic state. The aldehyde branch is chemically motivated but remains a connective representation of a transiently implied species rather than a claim of isolated high-yield production (Patel et al., 2015; Miller & Schlesinger, 1993)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Ammonia addition to cyanohydrin 26 gives valine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (copper sulfide / Cu2S-like)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface concentration on clay in a cyanosulfidic setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "post-photochemical NH3 addition; Patel intermediate 26 to 27; reported ~42% yield"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia substitutes into the activated branched cyanohydrin framework to generate the alpha-aminonitrile corresponding to valine.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. 2015 explicitly report conversion of intermediate 26 to valine aminonitrile 27 upon NH3 addition, with approximately 42% yield. This is one of the strongest experimentally supported surface routes to the immediate valine precursor and is represented directly (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Classical alkaline Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde to valine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite-like)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration and imine stabilization on drying surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral-to-basic pH ~8-10; concentrated cyanide/ammonia in evaporitic or geothermal pools"}, "mechanism": "Isobutyraldehyde forms an imine with NH3, cyanide adds to the imine, and the branched alpha-aminonitrile is formed.", "reasoning": "The deep research identifies the canonical Strecker route as a primary validated pathway to valine and states explicitly that isobutyraldehyde is the Strecker precursor to valine. High-pH, cyanide-rich surface settings are literature-consistent for classical Strecker chemistry. Mineral participation is included here as concentration/alignment support, while acknowledging that the core mechanism is solution-phase condensation (Miller & Schlesinger, 1993; Powner et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "DAP-enabled neutral-water Strecker variant from isobutyraldehyde to valine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004", "mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature to 300K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "diamidophosphate with phosphate-mineral-rich drying pools", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral pH; N-phosphoro-aminonitrile chemistry analogous to reported 73-quantitative% yields for favorable aldehydes"}, "mechanism": "DAP activates aldehyde/cyanide chemistry at near-neutral pH by transient phosphoro-aminonitrile formation, functionally bypassing the need for strongly basic free-ammonia conditions.", "reasoning": "Powner et al. 2019 showed that diamidophosphate promotes Strecker-type phosphoroaminonitrile formation in neutral water in high yield from simple aldehydes. The deep research specifically states that by analogy this chemistry could enable valine formation from isobutyraldehyde under mild conditions. This step is therefore included as a literature-supported variant, but the reasoning explicitly recognizes that direct valine-specific yield data are analogical rather than fully demonstrated (Powner et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_0