wed list, Fe0 and mackinawite are included as geochemically compatible co-agents, but the conditions and justification explicitly preserve the critical literature fact that Ni-bearing catalysts are essential and experimentally validated; no catalyst-free reaction is implied (Kaur et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Biochemical-style transamination equilibrium between valine and alpha-ketoisovalerate", "inputs": ["mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "mineral interface or pool chemistry; reversible amino acid/keto acid interconversion represented as network linkage"}, "mechanism": "Valine can be deaminated/transaminated to its cognate alpha-keto acid, establishing a proto-metabolic branch-point.", "reasoning": "The deep research explicitly notes that alpha-ketoisovalerate is the transamination product of valine and participates in these networks. This reversible link is included to connect hydrothermal reductive amination chemistry with broader prebiotic proto-metabolic interconversion and to satisfy the requirement for cross-environment flow without inventing unsupported new precursor chemistry. It is a network-connecting biochemical analogue rather than a claim of selective abiotic high-yield synthesis under one fixed condition (Miller & Schlesinger, 1993; Kaur et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Spark-discharge direct formation of valine in complex atmospheric mixtures", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_003", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_004", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "800-1200C transient discharge, then cooling", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface mineral concentration after atmospheric synthesis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing gas mixture analogue; lightning/plasma energy; complex multicomponent product distribution"}, "mechanism": "Electrical discharge generates a complex organic mixture in which amino acids, including valine, appear along with cyanide and carbonyl precursors.", "reasoning": "Johnson et al. 2009 reported direct detection of valine and isovaline in reanalyzed Miller discharge residues. This node is intentionally represented as a complex-mixture source of valine, not as a mechanistically selective single-step synthesis. It addresses prior feedback by including the correct atmospheric feedstocks rather than NH3 alone. Surface mineral agents again denote post-rainout concentration and preservation in shallow pools, consistent with the environmental interpretation given in the deep research (Johnson et al., 2009)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Patel full cyanosulfidic route", "description": "Canonical literature-based cyanosulfidic homologation from atmospheric HCN/formaldehyde feedstocks through glyceraldehyde, acetone, cyanohydrin/thioamide intermediates, valine cyanohydrin 26, valine aminonitrile 27, and finally valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_013", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Patel route seeded from pre-existing glyceraldehyde", "description": "Surface cyanosulfidic synthesis beginning from glyceraldehyde already present in a pond or delivered from prior sugar chemistry, then proceeding through acetone and the validated Patel valine-aminonitrile sequence.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_013", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Patel route seeded from acetone", "description": "A shortened cyanosulfidic branch using acetone as the entry carbonyl, matching the experimentally important acetone