epends on advanced precursor availability, but as a terminal validated segment it is strong.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"State explicitly that this pathway evaluates only the terminal literature-demonstrated conversion sequence.\",\n        \"Provide more detail on hydrolysis conditions for aminonitrile-to-amino-acid conversion.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.84\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.87,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.9,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.86,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.91,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n      \"feedback\": \"The classical Strecker route from isobutyraldehyde to valine aminonitrile and then hydrolysis to valine is chemically standard and literature-supported. The major issue is not the chemistry itself but precursor availability: the research explicitly identifies isobutyraldehyde supply as a central open problem. As drawn, the route is good if isobutyraldehyde is available.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Add pH information emphasizing alkaline conditions needed for free NH3.\",\n        \"Make explicit that this route is bottlenecked by the uncertain prebiotic source of isobutyraldehyde.\",\n        \"If aiming for full network realism, include a justified source or environmental concentration mechanism for the aldehyde.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.84\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.81,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.87,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.91,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n      \"feedback\": \"The DAP-enabled Strecker variant is a reasonable literatu